  <content>
    <title>Strategy Analysis: Business Need Framing</title>

    <summary>Strategy Analysis starts by defining why change is needed. The business need must be outcome-shaped — not solution-shaped — and must carry drivers with primary-source evidence, a falsifiable consequence of inaction, a named decision-maker, a time horizon, and explicit traces to corporate strategic goals. A need frame signed by the sponsor is the gate to current-state work.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Projects start without understanding why. Solutions are built without connecting to business goals. After delivery, nobody can explain the business value. Initiatives compete for resources without clear prioritization criteria. The gap between strategy and execution is wide.</p>
      <p>Without a defensible business need frame: solutions are disconnected from goals, business value is unclear, initiative prioritization is political not analytical, and resources are wasted on the wrong problems. BABOK Knowledge Area 6 (Strategy Analysis) establishes that every initiative must begin with an understood and agreed business need before any solution is proposed.</p>
      <p>The most common failure mode is a solution dressed as a need: "we need a new CRM" instead of "we need to reduce time-to-resolution from 8h to 2h." LLMs and humans alike default to solution-shaped framing; the frame agent must actively refuse it.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>A new initiative is starting and a sponsor has handed the BA a vague mandate ("we need to fix customer service") — you need a defensible problem frame before any solution is proposed.</item>
        <item>Annual or quarterly portfolio planning where N candidate initiatives compete for the same budget and each needs a one-pager linking to a strategic goal, gap, and capability.</item>
        <item>Pre-RFP or pre-business-case work where the change strategy will gate a 7-figure spend; auditors and the steering committee will demand traceability from need to spend.</item>
        <item>Digital transformation programs where the business need spans process, tech, people, and data simultaneously.</item>
        <item>M&amp;A integration: acquired entity current state vs. post-merger future state, with a gap analysis driving Day-1 / Day-100 / Day-365 plans.</item>
        <item>Regulatory-driven change (SOX, GDPR, DORA, NIS2): the regulator defines the future state externally; the BA must produce the need frame and gap.</item>
        <item>After a strategy refresh by leadership: each function translates the new corporate strategy into its own future-state and gap, and the BA agents help pull the workstreams onto a shared template.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-team, single-quarter, low-blast-radius work — a 5-line ADR plus a backlog item beats a strategy artifact.</item>
        <item>The future state is already locked by an executive who is not interested in alternatives — document it as a directive instead; producing a "strategy analysis" becomes theatre.</item>
        <item>Pure incident response or outage post-mortems — those use root-cause analysis, not future-state-vs-current-state framing.</item>
        <item>Early-stage product discovery where customer pain is unproven — use opportunity-solution-trees, jobs-to-be-done, or lean-canvas first, then strategy analysis once the opportunity is validated.</item>
        <item>Pure financial decisions with directly comparable cash flows — go to NPV / IRR; don't dress them as strategy analysis.</item>
        <item>Operational hot-fixes with a known cause and known patch — overhead exceeds value.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <how-to>
      <step>Read all sponsor briefs, steering minutes, and exec memos available. Identify the raw mandate.</step>
      <step>Test every candidate need statement: does it describe an outcome the organization must achieve, or a solution to implement? Reject solution-shaped statements. Re-elicit: "What business result would tell you this problem is solved?"</step>
      <step>Assemble the need statement in the canonical form: "[Organization] needs to [accomplish something] because [reason/driver]. If not addressed, [consequence]." Keep it under 30 words.</step>
      <step>For each driver, locate a primary source quote (steering minute, regulator publication, the org's own telemetry). No driver without evidence. Stamp retrieved_at on external sources.</step>
      <step>Write the consequence of inaction in falsifiable terms (not "things will get worse" — quantify: "monthly churn will increase 3pp per quarter untreated").</step>
      <step>Identify the decision-maker: the named individual who can commit resources. If absent, flag as an ambiguity and do not proceed to current-state work.</step>
      <step>Trace every stated driver and goal to a corporate strategic goal ID (GOAL-XXX). If no trace exists, flag it — do not invent IDs.</step>
      <step>Circulate the need statement for sponsor sign-off. Need statement signed by sponsor is the human-in-the-loop checkpoint before current-state work begins.</step>
    </how-to>

    <rules>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The business need statement MUST be outcome-shaped, not solution-shaped. Any statement containing "implement", "deploy", "build", "buy", or "migrate" MUST be recast as a measurable outcome before proceeding.</statement>
        <rationale>Solution-shaped needs hard-code a choice before the problem is understood. The BA and agents must refuse them because they collapse the solution space before the gap analysis has been done.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every driver MUST cite a primary-source verbatim quote with document name and date. Drivers without evidence MUST be flagged as unverified and excluded from the signed need statement.</statement>
        <rationale>Generic driver prose ("AI is disrupting industries") is ignored in steering reviews. Evidence-backed drivers survive scrutiny and give the BA standing to defend the need.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The consequence of inaction MUST be falsifiable and quantified where possible. Aspirational language ("things will deteriorate") MUST be rejected.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a measurable consequence of inaction, leadership cannot see the cost of doing nothing; the strategy reads as advocacy rather than analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>A named decision-maker MUST be identified before need-framing is complete. If no decision-maker is named, the need frame is not signed off; downstream agents MUST NOT begin current-state work.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a decision-maker, change strategy recommendations have no authority; the analysis floats until someone with budget and mandate takes ownership.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </rules>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>The BA owns framing and judgment; agents own coverage, traceability, and artifact production. For the need-framing phase, run a sonnet need-frame-agent that reads sponsor briefs and steering minutes and emits the following JSON:</p>
      <example type="good" title="Need-frame agent output schema">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[{
  "need_statement": "<= 30 words, outcome-shaped (NOT solution-shaped)",
  "drivers": [
    {"driver": "...", "source_quote": "...", "source_doc": "...", "retrieved_at": "YYYY-MM-DD"}
  ],
  "consequence_of_inaction": "<= 30 words, falsifiable",
  "decision_maker": {"name": "...", "role": "..."} ,
  "time_horizon": "Q|Y|multi-year",
  "strategic_goals_referenced": ["GOAL-XXX"],
  "ambiguities": ["<= 5 items"]
}]]></code>
        <note>Reject solution-shaped need statements; re-cast as outcome. Every driver cites a verbatim source_quote. If no GOAL-XXX trace exists, flag and do NOT invent IDs.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Solution-shaped need statement">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[We need a new CRM system to replace our current one.]]></code>
        <note>This is a solution, not a need. Recast: "We need to reduce customer time-to-resolution from 8h to 2h because churn is rising 3pp per quarter." Then trace to the corporate goal for customer retention.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-template">
      <prompt purpose="need-frame-agent system prompt">
        <![CDATA[
You are a BA strategy-analysis need-framer. Input: sponsor brief, steering
minutes, exec memos. Output strict JSON:
{
  need_statement: "<= 30 words, outcome-shaped (NOT solution-shaped)",
  drivers: [{driver, source_quote, source_doc, retrieved_at}],
  consequence_of_inaction: "<= 30 words, falsifiable",
  decision_maker: {name, role} | null,
  time_horizon: "Q|Y|multi-year",
  strategic_goals_referenced: [GOAL-XXX...],
  ambiguities: [<= 5 items]
}
Rules:
- Reject solution-shaped need ("we need a new CRM"). Re-cast as outcome
  ("we need to reduce time-to-resolution from 8h to 2h") or return an
  ambiguity flag.
- Every driver cites a verbatim source_quote. No driver without evidence.
- If no GOAL-XXX trace exists, flag and DO NOT invent IDs.
        ]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Solution dressed as need: "we need a new CRM" or "we need a new system".</description>
        <reason>Hard-codes a solution choice before the gap analysis has been done; blocks exploration of build/buy/partner/modify options.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Vague business need: "We need to be more efficient" or "We need to improve."</description>
        <reason>Unmeasurable needs cannot be used to validate future states, prioritize gaps, or track closure; they become political documents.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No strategic alignment: the initiative does not connect to any named corporate goal.</description>
        <reason>Initiatives without goal traces lose budget battles and get de-prioritized when resources are constrained.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Strategy analysis becomes the project: months of frame-current-future-gap iteration with no commitment.</description>
        <reason>Analysis-paralysis. Time-box every phase; publish v0.1 in days not weeks. Frame phase cap: 1 week.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>LLMs love proposing solutions; they will fill in "we should adopt X" given any need. The frame agent must be hard-prompted to refuse solutions and explicitly produce outcomes.</p>
      <p>Agents hallucinate GOAL-XXX traces. Validate every trace against the actual .aidocs/ strategy plus requirements catalog with git grep before persisting.</p>
      <p>Agents hallucinate stakeholders. Given a sparse brief, agents invent names. Pass the actual stakeholder list as input; reject any name the agent invents.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="artifacts">
      <p>Business Need Statement artifact carries: need statement, drivers with evidence, consequence of inaction, decision-maker, time horizon, strategic goal traces, success metrics, stakeholders affected, constraints. It is signed by the sponsor before current-state work begins. Each revision is a git commit with Conventional Commits format; git log is the rationale audit trail.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="references">
      <p>IIBA — BABOK Guide v3, Knowledge Area 6 Strategy Analysis (section 6.1 Analyze Current State, which establishes the need-framing prerequisite). Rumelt — Good Strategy / Bad Strategy (kernel: diagnosis before guiding policy; canonical antidote to fluff need statements). ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148:2018 Requirements Engineering (criteria and goal traceability discipline).</p>
    </section>

